Method 2
Option 1: Jira Data Center / Server (Self managed)
This is the most common and recommended setup because you have access to Jira logs.

Step 1: Enable detailed REST API logging in Jira
Jira uses Log4j for application logs.
1.1 Enable REST logging from Jira UI (recommended)
1.	Go to
Jira Admin → System → Logging and Profiling
2.	Add a new logger:

Field          	Value
Package name	  com.atlassian.jira.rest
Log level      	DEBUG

(Optional but useful)
•	com.atlassian.plugins.rest
•	com.atlassian.jira.web.filters.accesslog

✅ This will log:
•	REST endpoint
•	HTTP method
•	Response status
•	Execution time
•	Authenticated user (when available)

1.2 (Optional) Enable Access Logs for HTTP details
For full HTTP request/response visibility (URL, IP, status, latency):
Edit:
<JIRA_INSTALL>/conf/server.xml

Ensure AccessLogValve is enabled:
<Valve className="org.apache.catalina.valves.AccessLogValve"
       directory="logs"
       prefix="jira_access_log"
       suffix=".log"
       pattern="%h %l %u %t &quot;%r&quot; %s %b %D" />

Restart Jira.
✅ This captures:
•	Client IP
•	HTTP method
•	REST path
•	Status code
•	Response time

Step 2: Identify log files
Typical log locations:
Log Type	Path
Application logs	<JIRA_HOME>/log/atlassian-jira.log
Access logs	<JIRA_INSTALL>/logs/jira_access_log*.log

Step 3: Ship logs to Elastic (Filebeat)
Install Filebeat on the Jira node.
3.1 Filebeat input configuration
filebeat.yml
filebeat.inputs:
  - type: log
    enabled: true
    paths:
      - /var/atlassian/jira/log/atlassian-jira.log
      - /opt/atlassian/jira/logs/jira_access_log*.log
    fields:
      service: jira
      log_type: rest_api
    fields_under_root: true

3.2 (Recommended) Parse REST logs with processors
Example for access logs:
processors:
  - dissect:
      tokenizer: '%{client_ip} %{ident} %{user} [%{timestamp}] "%{method} %{url} %{protocol}" %{status} %{bytes} %{duration}'
      field: "message"
      target_prefix: "http"

3.3 Send logs to Elasticsearch
output.elasticsearch:
  hosts: ["http://elasticsearch:9200"]
  index: "jira-rest-logs-%{+yyyy.MM.dd}"

Restart Filebeat:
systemctl restart filebeat

Step 4: Configure Kibana
4.1 Create index pattern
In Kibana → Stack Management → Index Patterns
jira-rest-logs-*

Time field:
@timestamp

4.2 Useful Kibana queries (KQL)
All REST API calls
service : "jira" AND url : "/rest

Failed REST calls
status >= 400

Calls by user
user : "jirauser"
Slow REST APIs (>2 seconds)
duration > 2000000

4.3 Suggested dashboards
Create visualizations for:
•	REST calls per minute
•	Top REST endpoints
•	Error rate (4xx / 5xx)
•	Slowest APIs
•	Top calling users or IPs



